            </h3>


            <h2><strong>Run anything</strong>
            </h2>
        </div>
    </div>


    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-lg-12">
            <p>From the latest container run-times to custom hardware, no matter what your workloads operating system or hardware requirements are, Port.Direct can help manage it.</p>

            <p>Abstracting a physical machine using a compbination of hardware and software, Virtual Machines present virtual hardware (e.g., RAM, CPU, NIC,
            hard disks, etc.) to an operating system. Virtualization allows a single computer to be split into multiple virtual machines, allowing
            heterogeneous operating systems (e.g. Windows / Linux ) and applications to run in isolation, side-by-side on the same physical machine. Proven
            with years of enterprise workloads, modern virtualisation solutions offer execelent security, reliability and support while the operating system
            sees a consistent, normalized set of hardware regardless of the actual physical hardware components.</p>
            <p>
                Containers work at the operating system rather than hardware, providing an experiance similar to ‘Apps’ on Android or Apple devices. This
                means that just as a virtual machine thinks it is a ‘real’ computer, an application in a container thinks it has exclusive use of the
                host operating system’s kernel. This practice offers several of the advantages of virtualisation, while removing the major issue of
                performance overhead by significantly reducing the number of stages required to deliver the desired application in a repeatable and
                controlled manner.</p>
        </div>
    </div>


